1. What is Seaborn used for?

Seaborn simplifies statistical data visualization in Python with attractive defaults and high-level functions built on Matplotlib, making complex plots accessible with minimal code.
1. Seaborn Purpose

Seaborn creates statistical graphics like heatmaps, violin plots, and pair plots for data analysis. Perfect for exploring datasets quickly with publication-ready visuals.​

Common uses:

    Correlation heatmaps (multicollinearity detection)

    Distribution plots (outliers + skewness)

    Box plots (comparing groups)

    Regression plots (trends + confidence intervals)



2. Why is Seaborn preferred over Matplotlib?

| Aspect             | Matplotlib            | Seaborn                               |
| ------------------ | --------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Code length        | 20+ lines for boxplot | 1 line: sns.boxplot()                 |
| Default style      | Basic, manual styling | Beautiful themes out-of-box           |
| Statistical plots  | Manual calculations   | Built-in (violin, swarm) newhorizons​ |
| Pandas integration | Manual data prep      | Direct df.plot()                      |


Example comparison:

python
# Matplotlib (verbose)
plt.boxplot(df['salary'])
plt.title("Salary Distribution")

# Seaborn (1 line)
sns.boxplot(y=df['salary'])



3. Which plot is best to find outliers?

Box plots reveal outliers automatically (1.5 × IQR rule):

text
Median: Middle line
Box: 25th-75th percentile (middle 50%)
Whiskers: 1.5×IQR range
Dots: Outliers (CEOs, interns)

HR Salary example:

Box plot shows:
• Typical range: ₹5-12L
• Outliers: 2 CEOs (₹45L), 3 interns (₹2L)

python
sns.boxplot(y=df['salary'])
# Instantly reveals salary anomalies



